# AI/LLM Integration Patterns

## Provider Abstraction

Never couple business logic to a specific AI provider. Use a service interface:

```typescript
// src/services/ai/types.ts
export interface AIProvider {
  generateStructuredOutput<T>(params: {
    prompt: string;
    schema: ZodSchema<T>;
    model?: string;
    maxTokens?: number;
  }): Promise<T>;
}

// src/services/ai/openai-provider.ts   — implements AIProvider
// src/services/ai/anthropic-provider.ts — implements AIProvider
// src/services/ai/google-provider.ts    — implements AIProvider
// src/services/ai/provider.ts           — factory that returns the active provider
```

- All AI calls go through the `AIProvider` interface
- Provider selection via env var (`AI_PROVIDER=openai|anthropic|google`) for system default
- Swap providers without touching business logic

## Bring Your Own API Key (BYOAK)

Registered users can supply their own API key for a supported LLM provider. This gives them provider choice, unlimited AI calls (billed to their own account), and access to premium models.

### Supported Providers

| Provider | Models Available | Env Var (System Key) |
|----------|-----------------|---------------------|
| OpenAI | gpt-4o, gpt-4o-mini, gpt-4-turbo | `OPENAI_API_KEY` |
| Anthropic | claude-3.5-sonnet, claude-3-haiku | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` |
| Google | gemini-1.5-pro, gemini-1.5-flash | `GOOGLE_AI_API_KEY` |

New providers are added by implementing `AIProvider` and registering in the factory — no business logic changes needed.

### Provider Resolution Chain

```typescript
// src/services/ai/provider.ts
export async function resolveProvider(userId?: string): Promise<{
  provider: AIProvider;
  source: "user" | "system";
}> {
  // 1. If authenticated, check for user-provided key
  if (userId) {
    const userKey = await getUserApiKey(userId);
    if (userKey) {
      return {
        provider: createProvider(userKey.provider, decrypt(userKey.encrypted_key)),
        source: "user",
      };
    }
  }

  // 2. Fall back to system default
  return {
    provider: createProvider(env.AI_PROVIDER, getSystemKey(env.AI_PROVIDER)),
    source: "system",
  };
}
```

- **User key takes priority** — if the user configured a key, always use it
- **System key fallback** — guests and users without keys use the platform's key
- **Source tracking** — track whether user or system key was used (for rate limiting decisions)

### Key Lifecycle

1. **Add key** — user selects provider, pastes API key in Settings
2. **Validate** — server makes a lightweight test call (e.g., list models) to verify the key works
3. **Encrypt & store** — AES-256-GCM encrypt with server-side `API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_SECRET`, store in `user_api_keys`
4. **Use** — on each AI call, decrypt at call time, pass to provider, never cache decrypted key
5. **Rotate** — user can update the key at any time; old key is overwritten
6. **Remove** — user can delete their key to revert to system defaults

### Rate Limiting with BYOAK

| User Type | Daily Match Limit | AI Provider |
|-----------|------------------|-------------|
| Guest | 3 | System key |
| Free (no BYOAK) | 10 | System key |
| Free (with BYOAK) | Unlimited | User's own key |
| Lifetime | Unlimited | User's key or system key |

- Users with their own key bypass AI-related rate limits (they're paying the provider directly)
- Abuse limits still apply (e.g., max 1000 requests/day to prevent runaway automation)

### Model Selection

- Users with BYOAK can select from available models for their chosen provider
- Default model per provider is pre-selected (cheapest that meets quality needs)
- Model selection stored in `user_api_keys.preferred_model`
- Business logic never assumes a specific model — always parameterized via the provider interface

## Cost Control (Critical for MVP)

- **Token budgets**: set `maxTokens` on every call — never leave unbounded
- **Model tiering**: use cheapest model that meets quality needs
  - Parsing/extraction: `gpt-4o-mini` or `claude-3-haiku` (fast, cheap)
  - Complex matching/scoring: `gpt-4o` or `claude-3.5-sonnet` (only when needed)
- **Cache AI responses**: hash the input, cache the output in Supabase for identical requests
- **Batch processing**: queue and batch multiple items when possible instead of one-at-a-time
- **Rate limiting**: enforce per-user daily limits on AI-powered features

## Structured Output (Always)

Never parse free-text AI responses. Always use structured output:

```typescript
const resumeDataSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string(),
  email: z.string().email().optional(),
  skills: z.array(z.string()),
  experience: z.array(z.object({
    title: z.string(),
    company: z.string(),
    years: z.number(),
  })),
});

const parsed = await aiProvider.generateStructuredOutput({
  prompt: buildResumeParsingPrompt(rawText),
  schema: resumeDataSchema,
});
```

- Zod schemas validate AI output — reject and retry on parse failure
- Max 2 retries per AI call, then fail gracefully with user notification

## Prompt Management

```
src/services/ai/
  prompts/
    resume-parsing.ts        # Prompt templates as functions
    skill-matching.ts
    job-description-analysis.ts
  types.ts                   # AIProvider interface + shared types
  provider.ts                # Provider factory + BYOAK resolution
  openai-provider.ts
  anthropic-provider.ts
  google-provider.ts
  key-management.ts          # Encrypt/decrypt/validate user API keys
```

- Prompts are **TypeScript functions** that accept typed parameters — never raw strings
- Keep prompts version-controlled and testable
- Include few-shot examples in prompts for consistent output quality
- System prompts define role and constraints; user prompts provide the data

## Reliability Patterns

1. **Timeout**: 30s max per AI call — abort and return graceful error
2. **Retry**: exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s) on transient errors (429, 500, 503)
3. **Fallback**: degrade to simpler analysis if AI is unavailable (keyword matching)
4. **Circuit breaker**: after 5 consecutive failures, stop calling for 60s
5. **Async processing**: long AI tasks (full resume analysis) run as background jobs, notify on completion

## Security

- Never send raw user PII in prompts when avoidable — anonymize or redact
- AI responses are untrusted input — validate and sanitize before storing or displaying
- Log prompt templates and token usage, never log full prompt content with user data
- System API keys for AI providers stored as server-only env vars (never `NEXT_PUBLIC_`)
- **User API keys**: encrypted at rest (AES-256-GCM), decrypted only in-memory at call time
- Never log, cache, or expose user API keys — treat as equivalent to passwords
- `API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_SECRET` env var required for BYOAK — must be a 32-byte hex string
- If decryption fails (key rotation, corruption), prompt user to re-enter their key
